{"id":"1708.05530","submitter":"Vladimir Kostov","authors":"Vladimir Petrov Kostov","title":"Polynomials, sign patterns and Descartes' rule of signs","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Mathematica Bohemica 144 (2019), No. 1, 39-67","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  By Descartes' rule of signs, a real degree $d$ polynomial $P$ with all\nnonvanishing coefficients, with $c$ sign changes and $p$ sign preservations in\nthe sequence of its coefficients ($c+p=d$) has $pos\\leq c$ positive and\n$neg\\leq p$ negative roots, where $pos\\equiv c($\\, mod $2)$ and $neg\\equiv\np($\\, mod $2)$. For $1\\leq d\\leq 3$, for every possible choice of the sequence\nof signs of coefficients of $P$ (called sign pattern) and for every pair $(pos,\nneg)$ satisfying these conditions there exists a polynomial $P$ with exactly\n$pos$ positive and exactly $neg$ negative roots (all of them simple). For\n$d\\geq 4$ this is not so. It was observed that for $4\\leq d\\leq 10$, in all\nnonrealizable cases either $pos=0$ or $neg=0$. It was conjectured that this is\nthe case for any $d\\geq 4$. We show a counterexample to this conjecture for\n$d=11$. Namely, we prove that for the sign pattern $(+,-,-,-,-,-,+,+,+,+,+,-)$\nand the pair $(1,8)$ there exists no polynomial with $1$ positive, $8$ negative\nsimple roots and a complex conjugate pair.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 18 Aug 2017 08:00:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-05-10"}
{"id":"1708.05531","submitter":"Takashi Goda","authors":"Michael B. Giles, Takashi Goda","title":"Decision-making under uncertainty: using MLMC for efficient estimation\n  of EVPPI","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Statistics and Computing, Volume 29, Issue 4, 739-751, 2019","doi":"10.1007/s11222-018-9835-1","report-no":null,"categories":"math.NA","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In this paper we develop a very efficient approach to the Monte Carlo\nestimation of the expected value of partial perfect information (EVPPI) that\nmeasures the average benefit of knowing the value of a subset of uncertain\nparameters involved in a decision model. The calculation of EVPPI is inherently\na nested expectation problem, with an outer expectation with respect to one\nrandom variable $X$ and an inner conditional expectation with respect to the\nother random variable $Y$. We tackle this problem by using a Multilevel Monte\nCarlo (MLMC) method (Giles 2008) in which the number of inner samples for $Y$\nincreases geometrically with level, so that the accuracy of estimating the\ninner conditional expectation improves and the cost also increases with level.\nWe construct an antithetic MLMC estimator and provide sufficient assumptions on\na decision model under which the antithetic property of the estimator is well\nexploited, and consequently a root-mean-square accuracy of $\\varepsilon$ can be\nachieved at a cost of $O(\\varepsilon^{-2})$. Numerical results confirm the\nconsiderable computational savings compared to the standard, nested Monte Carlo\nmethod for some simple testcases and a more realistic medical application.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 18 Aug 2017 08:02:24 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 15 Sep 2017 01:39:12 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Tue, 31 Oct 2017 06:25:41 GMT"},{"version":"v4","created":"Mon, 19 Mar 2018 07:31:16 GMT"}],"update_date":"2019-12-09"}
