{"id":"1708.07407","submitter":"Suresh Tiwari dr","authors":"S C Tiwari","title":"Do phonons carry spin?","comments":"Literature survey shows that already in 1988 McLellan discussed\n  phonon angular momentum. The abstract and Introduction are revised in this\n  light. Appendix and four new references added to address some questions","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Recently the question of phonon angular momentum has been raised : phonon\nangular momentum in a magnetic crystal could play an important role in the\nangular momentum balance in the Einstein-de Haas effect. This proposition is\nquite natural and understandable, however the idea of phonon spin seems\nambiguous in the literature. In 1988 McLellan presented phonon angular momentum\nstates for circular and elliptical polarizations of phonons that represent\norbital angular momentum and also pointed out analogy to isotropic quantum\nharmonic oscillator. In view of its fundamental importance we investigate this\nissue and conclude that phonon spin hypothesis is physically untenable, and the\nphonon angular momentum has to be interpreted as orbital. The photon-phonon\nanalogy is also misleading. It is argued that Cosserat elastic medium having\ninternal torque may have lattice excitations different from phonons having spin\none or spin two that we term as Cosseratons. In addition a new source of\nangular momentum balance originationg from anomalous electron magnetic moment\nis suggested.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 18 Aug 2017 07:33:11 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 19 Oct 2017 08:10:59 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Sat, 11 Nov 2017 10:10:57 GMT"}],"update_date":"2017-11-15"}
